################################################################################################
#
# The aim of the project is to filter out FASTQ reads which have less than 30 base fragment  
# of the sequence of interest (the reminder of a read is a fragment of the vector sequence). 
#
################################################################################################ 
#
# The vector is cirular, encompassing the te sequence of interest from both ends. We arbitrarly 
# define the ends as LEFT and RIGHT. The following ends of the vector are not 'real', 
# for the real-world use they are
# to be replaced by the sequence consisting of the e.g. HindIII site plus n bases of the vector 
# adding up to e.g. 50 bases.
# LEFT: 	GGGAGGCCG 
# RIGHT: 	CCTCCCATA
# TODO: method to be extended to accommodate LEFT_RC:CGGCCTCCC and RIGHT_RC: 	TATGGGAGG
#
################################################################################################
#
# INPUT: a FASTQ reads file (assuming single-end reads, but can be easily extended to paired-end) 
# OUTPUT: a FASTQ reads file, withthout the reads containing < 30 bases of sequence of interest
#
##################################################################################################
#
# USAGE: call make input_filename_fastq
#
##################################################################################################

    

